label: University of Pennsylvania Ms. Codex 920: Grammatica latina
attribution: Provided by the University of Pennsylvania Libraries
description:
Summary: Treatise on Latin grammar, based on the teachings of Aristotle. Such a work is typical of medieval and Renaissance education theory, which combined topics like logic and rhetoric as well as syntax and grammar under the label of grammatica.
        Language: Latin
        Support: paper
        Extent: 
        Collation: Paper, i + 38 + i; 1-2¹⁰ 3⁸ 4¹⁰; 1-5, [v], 6-10, [v], 11-14, [iv], 15-19, [v]; contemporary foliation in ink, lower right recto; quires signed a-d on numbered pages.
        Layout: Written in 30 long lines, ruled in light ink.
        Script: Written in a semigothic cursive script.
        Decoration: Sprinkled edges; guide letters in margins for missing decorated initials.
        Binding: Modern boards.
        Origin: Written in Germany in 1460 (Zacour-Hirsch).
        Cite as:	
        UPenn Ms. Codex 920
        For catalog record, see Permanent Link: 4226583 http://hdl.library.upenn.edu/1017/d/medren/4226583
  For TEI description and digital images, see: http://openn.library.upenn.edu/Data/PennManuscripts/html/mscodex920.html
